Chapter 6: Applications and Extensions

6.1 Quantum Machine Learning: Avoiding Barren Plateaus

The free independence design principle suggests that quantum neural networks built from blocks with freely independent generators (e.g., using random unitaries with semicircular spectral distributions) maintain a constant gradient variance as the number of qubits grows. We validate this numerically with small-scale simulations (up to 20 qubits) using the NPA hierarchy to compute gradient variances for typical loss functions. Results confirm that free architectures avoid the exponential decay observed in generic random circuits.

6.2 Cognitive Modeling: Predicting Order Effects

We replicate the classic Clinton‑Gore survey order‑effect experiment [Busemeyer & Bruza, 2012] using a two‑qubit model. The two questions are represented by non‑commuting projections $P_1$, $P_2$ on $M_2(\mathbb{C})$, and the prior state $\rho$ is chosen to fit the empirical joint probabilities. The model predicts the order‑difference $\mathbb{P}(Q_1=yes, Q_2=yes) - \mathbb{P}(Q_2=yes, Q_1=yes) = \operatorname{Tr}(\rho[P_1,P_2])$. Using the experimentally observed values, we estimate the commutator norm and compare with the theoretical bound. This provides a quantitative test of the non‑commutative inference framework.

6.3 The Algorithmic Maakoul Gap

Definition 6.3.1. The Algorithmic Maakoul Gap is
\Delta\mathfrak{M}(\mathcal{A}) = \sup_\beta \left( \frac{B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)}{B_{\text{class}}(\beta)} - 1 \right).

Theorem 6.3.2. For any communication graph $G$ containing a cycle, $\Delta\mathfrak{M} > 0$. The gap is maximized when the local algebras are Type III (continuous‑variable systems).

Corollary 6.3.3. Classical emulation of a non‑commutative system with gap $\Delta\mathfrak{M}$ requires at least $C_{\text{class}} \ge \exp(\Omega(\Delta\mathfrak{M} \cdot \log N))$ bits of communication per update.

Proof (sketch). The quantum correlation set $\mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}$ has exponentially more extreme points than the classical polytope in the dimension of the Hilbert space. To approximate a point at distance $\Delta\mathfrak{M}$ from the classical set, one needs to sample exponentially many classical bits. □

