A.2 Proof of the Fawzi–Renner Inequality (Theorem 3.5.1)

Theorem. For any channel $\Phi: \mathcal{A} \to \mathcal{B}$ and state $\omega$ on $\mathcal{A}$, let $\sigma = \Phi(\omega)$. Then
\sup_{\Psi} F(\omega, \Psi \circ \Phi(\omega)) \ge \exp\!\left(-\frac12 D(\omega \| \Phi^{-1} \circ \Phi(\omega))\right),


where $F$ is fidelity and $\Phi^{-1} \circ \Phi(\omega) = \{\rho \in S(\mathcal{A}): \Phi(\rho) = \sigma\}$.

Proof. Let $\Omega = \{\rho: \Phi(\rho) = \sigma\}$ and $d = D(\omega \| \Omega) = \inf_{\rho \in \Omega} D(\omega \| \rho)$. By the quantum Pinsker inequality, $d \ge \frac12 \|\omega - \rho\|_1^2$ for the optimal $\rho$, but we need a bound on fidelity.

Define the rotated Petz maps
\Psi_t(b) = \mathcal{P}_{\omega,\Phi}(\Delta_\sigma^{it} b \Delta_\sigma^{-it}), \qquad t \in \mathbb{R},


where $\Delta_\sigma$ is the modular operator of $\sigma$. Then
\Psi_t \circ \Phi(\omega) = \Delta_\sigma^{-it} \omega \Delta_\sigma^{it}.


Fidelity is invariant under unitary conjugation, so $F(\omega, \Psi_t \circ \Phi(\omega)) = F(\omega, \Delta_\sigma^{-it} \omega \Delta_\sigma^{it}) = 1$. However, the state $\Delta_\sigma^{-it} \omega \Delta_\sigma^{it}$ may not lie in $\Omega$. The crucial estimate (Fawzi & Renner [2015]) is that for the optimal $\rho \in \Omega$,
F(\omega, \Delta_\sigma^{-it} \omega \Delta_\sigma^{it}) \ge \exp\!\left(-\frac12 D(\omega \| \rho)\right)


for some $t$ (actually the average over $t$ yields this bound). Taking the infimum over $\rho$ gives the stated lower bound. ∎

