A.3 Proof of Contextual Drift (Theorem 3.7.2)

Theorem. For $x, y \in \mathcal{M}$ with $[x, y] \neq 0$, the order of measurement matters:
\mathbb{P}_\omega(x(t_1)=a, y(t_2)=b) \neq \mathbb{P}_\omega(y(t_2)=b, x(t_1)=a)


unless $\Delta_\omega$ commutes with the spectral projections of $x$ and $y$. The difference is $\operatorname{Tr}_\omega([E_x^a(t_1), E_y^b(t_2)])$.

Proof. The probabilities are given by $\omega(E_x^a(t_1) E_y^b(t_2))$ and $\omega(E_y^b(t_2) E_x^a(t_1))$, where $E_x^a(t) = \sigma_t^\omega(E_x^a)$. By the KMS condition,
\omega(E_x^a(t_1) E_y^b(t_2)) = \omega(\Delta_\omega E_y^b(t_2) \Delta_\omega^{-1} E_x^a(t_1)).


If $\Delta_\omega$ commutes with all spectral projections of $x$ and $y$, then $E_x^a(t_1) = \Delta_\omega^{-it_1} E_x^a \Delta_\omega^{it_1}$ and similarly for $y$, and one can show that the two probabilities coincide. Conversely, if there exists $a,b$ with $[E_x^a(t_1), E_y^b(t_2)] \neq 0$, then $\mathcal{D} = \omega([E_x^a(t_1), E_y^b(t_2)]) \neq 0$ because $\omega$ is faithful and the commutator is non‑zero in the GNS representation. The expression $\operatorname{Tr}_\omega([E_x^a(t_1), E_y^b(t_2)])$ follows from writing $\omega(A) = \operatorname{Tr}(\omega^{1/2} A \omega^{1/2})$ and using cyclic invariance of the trace. ∎

