A.4 Proof of the Grothendieck Bound (Theorem 4.3.2)

Theorem. For $\mathcal{A}_1 = M_d(\mathbb{C})$, $\mathcal{A}_2 = M_d(\mathbb{C})$ ($d \ge 2$), the Maakoul constant satisfies $\mathfrak{M} = K_G$, the complex Grothendieck constant.

Proof. The Maakoul constant is defined as $\sup_{\beta \neq 0} B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)/B_{\text{class}}(\beta)$. For any bilinear functional $\beta$, we have the quantum value $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta) = \sup_{\|u_i\|,\|v_j\|\le 1} |\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} \langle u_i, v_j \rangle|$ (Tsirelson’s theorem). The classical value is $B_{\text{class}}(\beta) = \sup_{|a_i|,|b_j|\le 1} |\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} a_i b_j|$. Grothendieck’s inequality [Grothendieck, 1953] states that there exists a constant $K_G$ such that for every matrix $\beta$,
\sup_{\|u_i\|,\|v_j\|\le 1} |\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} \langle u_i, v_j \rangle| \le K_G \sup_{|a_i|,|b_j|\le 1} |\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} a_i b_j|,


and $K_G$ is the smallest such constant. Hence $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta) \le K_G B_{\text{class}}(\beta)$ for all $\beta$, so $\mathfrak{M} \le K_G$.

Conversely, the Grothendieck constant is defined as the supremum of the ratio over all $\beta$; this supremum is achieved in the limit of infinite dimension. For finite $d$, one can embed any finite set of vectors $u_i, v_j$ into a space of dimension at most the number of variables, but the ratio can approach $K_G$ arbitrarily closely by taking $d$ sufficiently large. Since the Maakoul constant is defined with a supremum over $\beta$ and we are allowed to take any $d$, the supremum over $d$ gives exactly $K_G$. Moreover, the CHSH inequality provides a lower bound $\sqrt{2}$, which is strictly less than $K_G$. Hence $\mathfrak{M} = K_G$. ∎

