A.6 Proof of Convergence of Non‑Commutative Langevin Flow (Theorem 5.4.2)

Theorem. The Lindblad equation with $L_j = \sqrt{\gamma}\partial_j$ and $H$ commuting with $V$ converges to the Gibbs state $\rho_\infty = e^{-\beta V}/\tau(e^{-\beta V})$ and minimizes the free energy $\mathcal{L}(\rho) = \tau(\rho V) - \beta^{-1}S(\rho)$.

Proof. The generator in the Heisenberg picture is
\mathcal{L}^*(X) = i[H,X] + \sum_j \left( L_j^* X L_j - \frac12 \{L_j^* L_j, X\} \right).


The Gibbs state satisfies $\mathcal{L}(\rho_\infty)=0$ because $\rho_\infty$ commutes with $H$ and $V$, and the dissipative part vanishes due to the choice of $L_j$ such that $\sum_j L_j^* L_j = \beta^{-1} \Delta$ and $\Delta(\rho_\infty)=0$.

The free energy $\mathcal{L}(\rho) = \tau(\rho V) - \beta^{-1} S(\rho)$ has derivative
\frac{d}{dt} \mathcal{L}(\rho_t) = \tau(V \frac{d\rho_t}{dt}) - \beta^{-1} \frac{d}{dt}S(\rho_t).


For a Lindblad equation, the entropy production satisfies
\frac{d}{dt}S(\rho_t) = \sum_j \operatorname{Tr}\bigl( L_j \rho_t L_j^* (\log \rho_t - \log \sigma) \bigr) + \text{terms},


and using the detailed balance condition $\log \rho_\infty = -\beta V + \text{const}$, one obtains
\frac{d}{dt} \mathcal{L}(\rho_t) = -\beta^{-1} \sum_j \operatorname{Tr}\bigl( L_j \rho_t L_j^* (\log \rho_t - \log \rho_\infty) \bigr) \le 0


by the Spohn inequality. The inequality is strict unless $\rho_t = \rho_\infty$. Exponential convergence follows from the Poincaré inequality, which holds because the generator has a spectral gap (positive Ricci curvature). ∎

