Appendix D: Tensor Network Representations for Non‑Commutative Inference

D.1 Matrix Product States (MPS)

For a 1D chain of $N$ sites with local dimension $d$, an MPS is
|\psi\rangle = \sum_{s_1,\dots,s_N} \operatorname{Tr}(A_1^{s_1} \cdots A_N^{s_N}) |s_1\cdots s_N\rangle,


where $A_i^{s}$ are $D \times D$ matrices (bond dimension $D$). For a mixed state $\rho$, one can use matrix product density operators (MPDO) or purify to an MPS.

D.2 Efficient Computation of Petz Map

Given a prior state $\rho$ as an MPS and a channel $\Phi$ that is local (e.g., a product of local maps), the Petz map $\mathcal{P}_{\omega,\Phi}$ can be approximated by applying the channel and then using a variational algorithm (e.g., DMRG) to invert it. This is feasible when the bond dimension remains moderate.

D.3 Complexity

The cost scales as $O(N D^3)$ per update, which is polynomial in $N$ if $D$ is bounded. This allows practical simulations for moderate system sizes.

