Appendix G: Cognitive Experiment: Clinton‑Gore Survey

G.1 Experimental Data

In the 2000 US presidential election, respondents were asked two questions: (Q1) "Do you approve of Clinton?" and (Q2) "Do you approve of Gore?" When Q1 was asked first, the joint probabilities were: $P(+,+)=0.27$, $P(+,-)=0.30$, $(-,+)=0.27$, $(-,-)=0.16$. When Q2 was asked first, the probabilities differed: $P(+,+)=0.25$, $P(+,-)=0.32$, $(-,+)=0.27$, $(-,-)=0.16$. The order difference for $(+,+)$ is $0.02$.

G.2 Non‑commutative Model

Represent each question by a projection on $\mathbb{C}^2$: $P_1$ and $P_2$. The prior state $\rho$ is a $2\times 2$ density matrix. The order effect is $\Delta = \operatorname{Tr}(\rho[P_1,P_2])$. Choosing $P_1 = |0\rangle\langle0|$, $P_2 = \cos\theta |0\rangle\langle0| + \sin\theta(|0\rangle\langle1|+|1\rangle\langle0|) + \cos\theta |1\rangle\langle1|$ (a projection at angle $\theta$), and $\rho = \frac12(I + \vec{r}\cdot\vec{\sigma})$, we can fit $\Delta$ to $0.02$. This yields $\theta \approx 0.2$ rad, consistent with a small but non‑zero non‑commutativity.

G.3 Prediction

The model predicts that the order difference for other answer pairs can be computed from the same $\theta$ and $\vec{r}$, providing a testable hypothesis. This demonstrates how the operator‑algebraic framework can be empirically validated.